Alison Buckholtz, alison@arl.org



RAY ENGLISH ELECTED SPARC STEERING COMMITTEE CHAIR

Oberlin=92s English Recently Named 2006 ACRL Librarian of the Year

Washington, DC =96 The SPARC Steering Committee, whose newest members=20
began their three-year terms on January 1, has elected Ray English to=20
the position of Chair.  English, the Azariah Smith Root Director of=20
Libraries at Oberlin College, has served as a SPARC Steering Committee=20=

member since 1999.

English was recently named the 2006 Association of College and Research=20=

Libraries=92 (ACRL) Academic/Research Librarian of the Year, an award=20
that recognizes an outstanding member of the library profession who has=20=

made a significant national or international contribution to=20
academic/research librarianship and library development.

=93SPARC is a dynamic, forward-focused and fast-paced organization that =
I=20
have greatly enjoyed working with since its founding, and I am pleased=20=

that I will have the opportunity as Chair to contribute to its=20
important work in the scholarly communication marketplace,=94 English=20
said.

=93Ray English is an original thinker who brings creativity and tactical=20=

leadership to the position of SPARC Chair,=94 said Heather Joseph,=20
SPARC=92s Executive Director.  =93Our steering committee and I believe =
he=20
will help move forward several important changes to benefit libraries,=20=

librarians, and researchers.=94

SPARC's voting membership, which includes representatives from over 150=20=

academic libraries in the U.S. and Canada, also elected the following=20
individuals to serve on the SPARC Steering Committee for three-year=20
terms which began January 1:

=95	Larry Alford, Temple University
=95	Sherrie Bergman, Bowdoin College (by re-election)
=95	Ray English, Oberlin College (by re-election)
=95	Diane Graves, Trinity University
=95	John Ober, University of California
=95	Sarah Pritchard, University of California, Santa Barbara

The new members join the current members of the SPARC Steering=20
Committee:

=95	Nancy Baker, University of Iowa
=95	Deb Carver, University of Oregon
=95	Gwendolyn Ebbett, University of Windsor
=95	Joyce Ogburn, University of Utah
=95	Carolyne Presser, University of Manitoba
=95	Bas Savenije, University of Utrecht

Steering Committee members whose terms concluded in December include=20
outgoing Chair Jim Neal (Columbia University), Sam Demas (Carleton=20
College), Sarah Michalak (UNC Chapel Hill), and MacKenzie Smith (MIT). =20=

Neal=92s service to the steering committee was recognized with a plaque=20=

and a speech from SPARC Executive Director Heather Joseph at the ALA=20
Midwinter Meeting in San Antonio.

The SPARC Nominating Committee for this year's election included=20
Shirley Baker, Charles Lowry, and Pamela Snelson.

***

SPARC
SPARC (Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition) and SPARC=20=

Europe are an international alliance of more than 300 academic and=20
research libraries working to correct imbalances in the scholarly=20
publishing system.  SPARC=92s advocacy, educational, and publisher=20
partnership programs encourage expanded dissemination of research.=20
SPARC is located on the Web at http://www.arl.org/sparc; SPARC Europe=20
is at
http://www.sparceurope.org.



